TERA – Minimal Physical Cognition Loop

Overview

This section describes a minimal, physically grounded model of cognition and iterative reasoning.

The system is defined by four components:

Paper — information storage

Desk — spatial organization

Lens — perception and filtering

Loop — temporal iteration


Together, they form a closed but adaptive reasoning structure.


---

System Definition

Let the system be defined as:

S = (I, R, P, T)

Where:

 = Information (Paper)

 = Spatial Context (Desk)

 = Perception / Filter (Lens)

 = Temporal Iteration (Loop)



---

Component Description

Paper — Information

Represents stored state.

records observations

preserves models

provides reference memory



---

Desk — Structure

Represents spatial organization.

arranges information

defines relationships

provides context



---

Lens — Perception

Represents selective observation.

filters input

defines focus

constructs interpretation



---

Loop — Time

Represents iterative dynamics.

enables repetition

allows correction

drives convergence or drift



---

System Behavior

The system evolves through repeated iteration:

I_{t+1} = f(I_t, P_t, R_t)

P_{t+1} = g(I_t, R_t)

R_{t+1} = h(I_t)

The loop introduces feedback:

S_{t+1} = \mathcal{L}(S_t)


---

Interpretation

This model describes cognition as a physically realizable process:

information is stored (Paper)

structure is arranged (Desk)

perception is applied (Lens)

iteration refines the system (Loop)



---

